success alert
Good job!
Agile projects welcome changes throughout the project. A very strict change process would suppress changes on the project.
Question 1:
Which of the following statements about agile projects is false?   

Good job!
The product owner is responsible for prioritizing the product backlog. The product owner represents the customers.
Question 2:
Who on an agile project is responsible for prioritizing the product backlog?   

success alert
Good job!
The sprint backlog is the output of the sprint planning meeting.
Question 3:
The team has completed the sprint planning meeting. What will be the output of that meeting?   

success alert
Good job!
The team is considered self-directing on an agile project.
Question 4:
The agile project team is considered:   

success alert
Good job!
The retrospective is a meeting conducted at the end of the sprint to reflect on what the team did correctly and what they did wrong and how to improve the next sprint.
Question 5:
The team is currently in a meeting discussing what went wrong and right during the sprint. What is the name of this meeting?   

Good job!
A release is a series of sprints (aka scrum) that results in a product the customers can start using.
Question 6:
What do you call multiple sprints that result in a shippable product?   

Good job!
Only a traditional project follows a strict change management process, while agile projects welcome changes throughout the project.
Question 7:
What is the difference between a traditional project scope and an agile project scope?  

success alert
Good job!
A daily stand-up meeting answers 3 questions: what they did yesterday, any obstacles they face, and what they plan to do today.
Question 8:
What does a daily stand-up meeting cover?   

success alert
Good job!
During a sprint review meeting, the customers will review the work completed in the sprint and give the team their feedback.
Question 9:
When is customer review work done on an agile project?   

success alert
Good job!
Agile teams prefer “low-tech high-touch.” This means more time with face-to-face conversions and physical interactions.
Question 10:
What tool would an agile team prefer?  

success alert
Good job!
Agile projects aim to deliver value early and often through incremental releases.
Question 11:
Agile projects aim to deliver value:

success alert
Good job!
On an agile project, the aim is to have as much stakeholder engagement as possible which will lead to more satisfied stakeholders.
Question 12:
What is critical on an agile project for it to be successful?

success alert
Good job!
Completed work is not considered waste, as it is work that will be given to the stakeholders to be used. All other choices are considered waste.
Question 13:
One of the values of managing an agile project is to reduce waste. Which of the following choices is not considered waste?

Good job!
Since agile projects deliver the product in increments, it is funded in increments. Traditional projects are generally funded at the beginning.
Question 14:
Funding on agile projects differ from traditional projects because agile projects are:

success alert
Good job!
Risk is considered anti-value. Risk represents threats that has the potential to reduce the value on a project, such as having features failing.
Question 15:
Which of the following is considered anti-value?

success alert
Good job!
Monopoly money is a prioritization technique where everyone is given equal monopoly money that have been distributed to the features based on value. All other choices are made-up.
Question 16:
While trying to engage the stakeholders on a project to prioritize the product backlog, the agile project manager has given the stakeholders fake money and told them to place a dollar value on the features based on their perception of value for that feature. What technique is this?

Good job!
Kano analysis will help to understand the customer’s level of satisfaction. They will classify the features based on their level of satisfaction such as the exciter’s, satisfiers, dissatisfiers, and indifferent.
Question 17:
What prioritization technique will have stakeholders categorize the features based on satisfiers and dissatisfied?

Good job!
Agile promotes the use of a minimal viable product. It refers to a set of functionalities that is complete to be useful but small enough not to be an entire project.
Question 18:
The software development team has completed a small module of the accounting software. They have released it to the customers. The module has very little features but is useful to the customers. This module represents:

Good job!
When using Kanban, the project team should ensure that they limit the work in progress on the Kanban board.
Question 19:
The project team has decided to implement Kanban. What should the team be most concerned about when using the Kanban methodology?

success alert
Good job!
The Gulf of evaluation occurs when, what one person described is often different from how another interpreted it.
